00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:05.530
NARRATOR:
The brain in old age.

00:03:05.530 --> 00:03:11.500
In its furrows and folds dwell
the imprints of a lifetime,

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:16.030
the unique history
that makes us who we are--

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:18.730
all we know and can remember

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:22.230
etched in
a hundred billion neurons--

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:25.860
cells that can last
our entire lives.

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:29.560
MAN:
Neurons can live to a hundred
and twenty-some years.

00:03:29.560 --> 00:03:31.530
What else will work
for that long

00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:34.230
without going to the repairman
all the time?

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:37.130
I think what's unusual
about the aging brain

00:03:37.130 --> 00:03:38.930
is the fact that it's built

00:03:38.930 --> 00:03:41.600
to withstand, you know,
that many years.

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:43.900
Somehow these neurons
just keep going.

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:51.260
And neurons are up against a
potentially hostile environment.

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:52.960
They take hits.

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:59.700
NARRATOR:
In its final decades,
the brain must contend

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:02.460
with the slowing down
of its neural circuits

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:05.260
and with crippling diseases
and injuries

00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:07.360
few younger brains ever face.

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:11.260
But scientists have begun

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:14.330
to unlock the secrets
of the aging brain.

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:20.360
Long thought to be defenseless
to the onslaughts of time,

00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:24.230
the brain can marshal
surprising powers of renewal.

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:57.560
NARRATOR:
Three years ago,
a stroke left Kent Miller

00:04:57.560 --> 00:05:00.060
with the left side
of his body paralyzed.

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:06.430
Even after months
of rehabilitation,

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:09.660
he still can't use
his left arm and hand.

00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:12.960
His career as an accountant
has come to an end.

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:18.260
MILLER:
You know, you feel worthless.

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:20.760
You can't do the things
that you used to do,

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:22.200
physically and mentally.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:26.100
And it's been a bear
for my wife, my family.

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:28.960
It hasn't been
too easy for me, either.

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:38.400
I want to become whole,
to put it simply.

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:40.700
I want to get my arm back.

00:05:40.700 --> 00:05:44.100
I want to take something
in my left hand.

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:46.700
I want to be able
to tie my shoes.

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:50.330
Is that, you know...
isn't that ridiculous--

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:53.560
63 years old
and can't tie your own shoes?

00:05:55.560 --> 00:05:58.330
I'm sick of Velcro.

00:05:58.330 --> 00:06:01.500
I want shoelaces, and I want
to be able to tie them.

00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:06.960
What about using a toothbrush
to brush your teeth?

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:09.130
Did you use
the affected hand
to do that?

00:06:09.130 --> 00:06:10.330
No, I didn't do that.

00:06:10.330 --> 00:06:11.930
You just used
your right hand.

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:12.930
Yeah.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:15.960
When you are
getting dressed,

00:06:15.960 --> 00:06:18.130
putting your arm
through a sleeve
of clothing,

00:06:18.130 --> 00:06:20.430
do you actively
push your left hand
and arm through,

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:22.060
or do you pull it on
with your right?

00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:24.030
I pull it on
with my right.

00:06:24.030 --> 00:06:25.600
So that means
your left hand

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:27.560
just kind of,
sort of,   
laid there?

00:06:27.560 --> 00:06:29.360
Yeah.

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:32.230
NARRATOR:
At the University of Alabama
in Birmingham,

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:33.860
Kent has enrolled in a study

00:06:33.860 --> 00:06:36.400
that may help him regain
the use of his arm.

00:06:37.960 --> 00:06:40.800
For Mr. Miller, he's still there
very much cognitively,

00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:43.860
but physically he would like
to have his independence back.

00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:46.300
So we're trying to work with him

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:49.830
so that he can regain
some of his independence.

00:06:49.830 --> 00:06:51.960
You know,
actually...

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:54.230
that's
fairly flexible.

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:56.530
Yeah, I know,
but<i> I</i> can't do it.

00:07:00.800 --> 00:07:05.500
NARRATOR:
The stroke that left Kent
with a paralyzed left arm

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:10.460
struck at the part of his brain
responsible for moving the arm.

00:07:10.460 --> 00:07:14.400
A blockage in an artery suddenly
stopped the flow of blood,

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:18.000
cutting off oxygen, shutting
down the flow of signals.

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:22.900
Millions of neurons were killed.

00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:25.200
Millions more were injured.

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:29.300
The damaged part of his brain
shrank to half its former size.

00:07:31.300 --> 00:07:34.030
Because the right side
of the brain controls

00:07:34.030 --> 00:07:35.730
the left side of the body,

00:07:35.730 --> 00:07:39.600
Kent's left arm and leg
were paralyzed.

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:43.530
MAN:
Most patients have been told,
after a stroke,

00:07:43.530 --> 00:07:45.400
that the amount of movement

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:49.860
that they have at six months
or one year

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:52.530
is the maximum
that they're going to have

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:54.330
for the rest of their life.

00:07:54.330 --> 00:07:56.660
Whatever they have
at one year, that's it

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:59.000
and they're not going
to get any better.

00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:05.800
NARRATOR:
But neuroscientist Edward Taub
and his colleagues

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:08.800
are teaching stroke survivors
from all over the country

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:11.460
how to revive the stricken part
of their brains

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:14.430
many years after a stroke.

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:16.030
Let it go.

00:08:16.030 --> 00:08:17.330
Let it go.

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:22.130
Extend that finger on out.

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:23.760
Good job.

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.660
There are little
spacings in here

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:26.960
for each individual
finger,

00:08:26.960 --> 00:08:28.060
so you're going
to have

00:08:28.060 --> 00:08:30.160
to push your hand
all the way in.

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:33.100
NARRATOR:
Taub's innovative therapy
requires Kent

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:34.900
to immobilize his good hand.

00:08:34.900 --> 00:08:36.460
Oh, let's do
this again.

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:40.160
What it boils down to is that
you can't use the good one,

00:08:40.160 --> 00:08:44.600
so you've got
to use the bad hand.

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:46.160
ALLEN:
Okay, are
you ready

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:48.300
to place your hand
up on the table?

00:08:48.300 --> 00:08:51.130
NARRATOR:
Kent had written off
his left hand as useless.

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:54.730
Now he will discover just
how much he can do with it--

00:08:54.730 --> 00:08:57.330
because of the resilience
of his brain.

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:01.400
During the past three years,

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:05.700
many of the injured neurons
have recovered.

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:09.230
But most have been recruited
by neighboring brain circuits

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:11.860
responsible for moving parts
of Kent's body

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:15.460
unaffected by the stroke.

00:09:15.460 --> 00:09:20.260
If Kent works hard enough, he
can force his recovered neurons

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:22.260
to resume their old job

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:25.830
and send signals
to his left arm once again.

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:29.700
But first he has to overcome
a dependence on his right arm

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:32.760
that's become deeply encoded
in his brain.

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:37.030
TAUB:
The person could use the arm,
if he really tried,

00:09:37.030 --> 00:09:39.200
but he just never tries.

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:43.260
He doesn't try
because he's learned not to try.

00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:45.230
It's a conditioned response,

00:09:45.230 --> 00:09:48.660
but it goes on week after week,
month after month

00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:52.930
and as time goes on, it becomes
more and more powerful,

00:09:52.930 --> 00:09:56.660
and eventually, it becomes
overwhelmingly powerful.

00:09:56.660 --> 00:09:59.730
And so you've got
to counter-condition

00:09:59.730 --> 00:10:03.860
this extremely strong tendency
not to use the arm.

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:06.530
I want you
to see how many
of these dominoes

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:08.300
you can flip over
in 30 seconds.

00:10:08.300 --> 00:10:11.430
The key is to not
just pick them up
and drop them,

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:13.360
but to actually
use your fingers

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:15.830
and maneuver
the domino.

00:10:15.830 --> 00:10:17.230
I know you have the ability.

00:10:17.230 --> 00:10:19.100
And that's what I'm here to do,

00:10:19.100 --> 00:10:21.400
to push you
to do the right thing.

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:23.560
Okay, let's go.

00:10:23.560 --> 00:10:24.560
You starting
the timer?

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:25.560
Yes.

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:29.900
Ooh, try it again.

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:30.930
That one was two.

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:32.630
That's okay.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:37.060
This last one you just did here,
we don't want that.

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:39.030
Better,
that's great.

00:10:39.030 --> 00:10:40.030
Ooh, look!

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:43.200
Those fingers
are working.

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:47.530
NARRATOR:
What makes Taub's therapy so
effective-- and so exhausting--

00:10:47.530 --> 00:10:49.560
is that these
small, clumsy movements

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:51.300
have to be endlessly repeated.

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:53.460
Nice.

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:54.630
Easy for you
to say.

00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:57.160
NARRATOR:
Over the next two weeks,

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:00.200
Kent will flip hundreds
of dominoes.

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:06.160
TAUB:
Simply overcoming this nonuse
of the limb isn't enough.

00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:12.330
You have to repeat movements
over and over and over again.

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:13.330
That's the secret.

00:11:13.330 --> 00:11:14.230
(<i> sighs</i> )

00:11:14.230 --> 00:11:15.230
Come on, fingers.

00:11:15.230 --> 00:11:16.230
(<i> groans</i> )

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:17.230
That's all right.

00:11:17.230 --> 00:11:18.260
Keep going.

00:11:18.260 --> 00:11:19.430
You put grease
on this one.

00:11:19.430 --> 00:11:21.930
(<i> laughs</i> )

00:11:21.930 --> 00:11:26.430
NARRATOR:
Hundreds of Taub's patients have
seen remarkable improvement.

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:31.100
James Faust was a sales manager

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:34.030
when a stroke paralyzed
his right arm.

00:11:34.030 --> 00:11:37.060
FAUST:
I had no use of it whatsoever.

00:11:37.060 --> 00:11:38.400
It was just dangling.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:39.860
I even had thoughts

00:11:39.860 --> 00:11:43.260
of maybe talking to somebody
about amputation

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:45.460
because it was just
in my way, really.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:54.860
NARRATOR:
But after two years
of paralysis,

00:11:54.860 --> 00:11:59.200
he went to see Edward Taub,
and his life turned around.

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:02.430
FAUST:
Two weeks or three weeks
after that program,

00:12:02.430 --> 00:12:04.660
we were out to eat dinner
one night.

00:12:04.660 --> 00:12:07.660
And I looked over at my wife,
and her eyes were wide

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:08.760
and her mouth was agasp...

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:09.900
(<i> imitates gasping</i> )

00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:11.460
And I said,
"What's the matter?"

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:14.230
And she said,
"Look at your right hand."

00:12:14.230 --> 00:12:17.530
And I did, and in that
right hand was a steak knife.

00:12:17.530 --> 00:12:19.330
And I was cutting up my steak

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:22.100
as if nothing had ever happened
to that hand.

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:27.630
NARRATOR:
Encouraged by his progress,

00:12:27.630 --> 00:12:30.560
Faust continued
his exercises for years.

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:35.230
FAUST:
I have no problem doing anything
I want to do with my right arm.

00:12:35.230 --> 00:12:37.700
I can drive my car.

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:40.330
I can tie my shoes.

00:12:40.330 --> 00:12:43.660
I can brush my teeth.

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:45.160
I can shave.

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:46.800
I can do anything I want to do.

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:54.830
TAUB:
The human brain is an
enormously plastic instrument.

00:12:54.830 --> 00:12:57.900
The amount of area of the brain

00:12:57.900 --> 00:13:01.730
that is involved
in producing movements

00:13:01.730 --> 00:13:07.760
or receiving sensation
keeps changing continuously,

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:14.200
based on the amount of use
that part of the body gets.

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:18.830
And it turns out that no matter
how old the person becomes--

00:13:18.830 --> 00:13:21.360
no matter
how aged the brain is--

00:13:21.360 --> 00:13:24.960
that plasticity
remains undiminished.

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:30.160
NARRATOR:
Taub has found that
after just two weeks of therapy,

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:32.860
the part of the brain
that controls the crippled limb

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:36.300
has expanded back
to its original size.

00:13:37.930 --> 00:13:42.000
Just why is still a mystery.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.330
TAUB:
In introductory
psychology courses

00:13:44.330 --> 00:13:46.060
when I first went to school,

00:13:46.060 --> 00:13:50.530
they used to say, some people
think of the brain as a muscle.

00:13:50.530 --> 00:13:54.200
And that was invariably followed
by the professor laughing

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:56.800
and saying,
"The brain isn't a muscle."

00:13:56.800 --> 00:13:59.360
Well, the fact
of the matter is...

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:02.030
(<i> chuckling</i> ):
that in the last 15 years,

00:14:02.030 --> 00:14:04.930
what we've begun to find
is that, in a sense,

00:14:04.930 --> 00:14:06.660
the brain<i> is</i> like a muscle

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:11.400
and the more that you
exercise it, the better it gets.

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:12.930
ALLEN:
Are those
good French fries?

00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:16.230
MILLER:
Yeah, they're
pretty good.

00:14:16.230 --> 00:14:18.700
NARRATOR:
After two weeks of therapy,

00:14:18.700 --> 00:14:21.430
Kent Miller is eating
with his left hand

00:14:21.430 --> 00:14:23.360
for the first time in years.

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:26.000
Break my neck
getting to it, though.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.560
ALLEN:
Good, good.

00:14:27.560 --> 00:14:29.730
That's good; good bite.

00:14:29.730 --> 00:14:34.000
MILLER:
I know I'm a lot farther along
than I was,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.830
because I really wouldn't use
my left hand.

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:41.400
When your hand gets tired,
stop, let it rest.

00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:45.660
MILLER:
It was so much easier to use
the right, which worked normal,

00:14:45.660 --> 00:14:48.330
and now it's...
it's almost natural

00:14:48.330 --> 00:14:51.560
for me to use it at times--
the left side.

00:14:51.560 --> 00:14:52.560
How's that?

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:53.960
That's a little
bit better.

00:14:53.960 --> 00:14:55.230
The one thing I got
to watch

00:14:55.230 --> 00:14:56.900
is that I don't bite
my fingers.

00:14:56.900 --> 00:14:59.330
Yeah, because you kind
of want to keep those.

00:14:59.330 --> 00:15:00.830
That's another thing.

00:15:00.830 --> 00:15:03.400
It's easier
to go down after something

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:05.830
than, sometimes,
lift the arm and...

00:15:05.830 --> 00:15:07.360
up to where it is.

00:15:07.360 --> 00:15:12.060
One of the things they want me
to do is to comb my hair,

00:15:12.060 --> 00:15:14.860
and I just can't hardly
get up there,

00:15:14.860 --> 00:15:17.060
where I can get
to my mouth okay.

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:21.730
And, uh... that's neat.

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:30.400
In this task,
I'm going to say
some words

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:32.660
that are the names
of objects
and animals.

00:15:32.660 --> 00:15:34.060
When...
Listen carefully

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:35.200
and when I finish,

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:37.200
I want you to say them
back to me

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:39.430
in the order of
their physical size--

00:15:39.430 --> 00:15:41.130
so from smallest
to largest.

00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:44.930
"Wastebasket, oven,
river,

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:49.000
slipper, lemon."

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:53.760
Slipper,
wastebasket, oven...

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:58.660
I don't know what the third...

00:15:58.660 --> 00:16:00.360
what the last one
you said there.

00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:02.000
I've forgotten it already.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.700
NARRATOR:
While only some of us suffer
from strokes,

00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:09.500
all of us worry our minds may
start to fail as we get older.

00:16:09.500 --> 00:16:12.460
I'd like you to point to the
same blocks in the same order.

00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:14.460
Here's the
first one.

00:16:14.460 --> 00:16:18.460
NARRATOR:
This lab at the
University of Michigan

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:22.130
studies how age
affects mental performance.

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:24.530
Its director,
psychologist Denise Park,

00:16:24.530 --> 00:16:27.400
is gathering evidence
that presents a new view

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:30.700
of brain aging.

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:34.600
Aging begins in your 20s,
as soon as you reach maturity.

00:16:34.600 --> 00:16:37.600
Our data show clearly--
absolutely clearly--

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:40.700
that, um, as you age
from 20 to 30,

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:43.160
you're a little bit slower.

00:16:43.160 --> 00:16:47.330
You process information
not quite as fast, um,

00:16:47.330 --> 00:16:51.560
you can hold a little bit less
information in consciousness

00:16:51.560 --> 00:16:55.230
and you recall a little,
tiny bit less from 20 to 30

00:16:55.230 --> 00:16:59.300
and from 30 to 40, the same
thing and so on and so forth.

00:17:02.630 --> 00:17:05.930
Then suddenly you're 70 and you
start really noticing, perhaps

00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:08.500
that these continuous declines
have aggregated

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:11.460
and you may realize

00:17:11.460 --> 00:17:14.760
that you're not cognitively
what you used to be.

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:22.800
Now, this is especially true
of memory,

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:24.830
and the more unfamiliar
the information,

00:17:24.830 --> 00:17:26.760
the more trouble
you're going to have.

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:28.730
You're going to remember
familiar stuff,

00:17:28.730 --> 00:17:30.200
but if I bring you in my lab

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:32.230
and ask you to remember
a list of words,

00:17:32.230 --> 00:17:34.560
you're going to see
that age-related decline.

00:17:34.560 --> 00:17:36.760
Okay, this task is
the free-recall task.

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:39.200
In this task, I'll
read you a list
of 12 words.

00:17:39.200 --> 00:17:40.360
When I get to...

00:17:40.360 --> 00:17:42.400
You should listen
carefully to the words,

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:43.800
and when I get
to the end,

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:45.600
you should recall them
back to me

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:47.100
in any order
that you like.

00:17:47.100 --> 00:17:48.330
Okay?

00:17:48.330 --> 00:17:50.800
All right.

00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:55.660
"Line, honey, train,

00:17:55.660 --> 00:18:03.900
"sky, puzzle, jury,
garage, doll,

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:10.930
wife, toast, bed, watch."

00:18:10.930 --> 00:18:13.260
Recall.

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:14.460
(<i> sighs</i> )

00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:23.530
Line, honey, train,
sky, doll, honey, um...

00:18:23.530 --> 00:18:28.300
Watch, honey...

00:18:28.300 --> 00:18:31.300
train...
I said that, didn't I?

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:39.360
Watch, toast, doll,
wife, honey, line...

00:18:41.960 --> 00:18:43.730
NARRATOR:
Learning someone's name,

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:45.860
remembering where you
parked your car...

00:18:45.860 --> 00:18:47.460
"Jury" comes to mind.

00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:50.500
NARRATOR:
Why do these things get harder
as we get older?

00:18:54.830 --> 00:18:58.260
One answer may lie in
the way new memories are formed.

00:19:00.530 --> 00:19:02.360
For a memory to take shape,

00:19:02.360 --> 00:19:05.560
neurons must forge
electrical and chemical links

00:19:05.560 --> 00:19:08.260
that connect them
into a stable circuit.

00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:14.830
For decades, scientists thought
that as the brain aged,

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:16.830
millions of neurons died,

00:19:16.830 --> 00:19:20.160
making it harder
for new circuits to form.

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:24.160
But in the 1990s,
this long-standing theory

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:26.300
was found to be wrong.

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:30.100
One of the most remarkable
things now that we understand it

00:19:30.100 --> 00:19:32.660
is how little nerve cell loss
there is--

00:19:32.660 --> 00:19:36.260
how much the brain stays full
of cells that we need

00:19:36.260 --> 00:19:38.430
in order to function normally,

00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:42.360
and that's something that
we didn't use to know at all.

00:19:42.360 --> 00:19:44.360
Now, this is interesting,

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:47.860
because it forces us, then,
to look elsewhere

00:19:47.860 --> 00:19:51.200
for the changes in the brain
that are impacting function.

00:19:51.200 --> 00:19:52.330
Hi, guys.

00:19:52.330 --> 00:19:54.160
How's the cutting
going?

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:55.300
Great.

00:19:55.300 --> 00:19:57.230
Are these the,
uh, brains
from Boston?

00:19:57.230 --> 00:20:00.600
NARRATOR:
At Mount Sinai School
of Medicine in New York,

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:03.730
neurobiologist John Morrison
is looking for clues

00:20:03.730 --> 00:20:06.600
in a region of the brain
where new memories are formed--

00:20:06.600 --> 00:20:08.600
the hippocampus.

00:20:11.430 --> 00:20:13.500
When we learn something new,

00:20:13.500 --> 00:20:17.230
neurons in the hippocampus
forge strong connections

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:19.760
by sending electrochemical
messages

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:23.660
across the tiny gaps
between them, called "synapses."

00:20:25.730 --> 00:20:28.300
Essential to the strength
of the connection

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:32.030
is the movement of electrically
charged particles of calcium

00:20:32.030 --> 00:20:33.900
drifting through the synapses.

00:20:35.300 --> 00:20:38.130
When the particles stream
into a neuron,

00:20:38.130 --> 00:20:40.230
they trigger chemical changes

00:20:40.230 --> 00:20:43.030
that make the connection
more reliable.

00:20:43.030 --> 00:20:45.730
The calcium flows
through a molecule

00:20:45.730 --> 00:20:49.800
that's the gateway to
the neuron-- the NMDA receptor.

00:20:49.800 --> 00:20:54.160
MORRISON:
We know that the NMDA receptor
is critically linked to memory.

00:20:54.160 --> 00:20:58.330
So, one of the changes that
leads to memory decline in aging

00:20:58.330 --> 00:21:01.160
might be lower levels
of NMDA receptors.

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:04.330
So we have looked
for those kinds of changes.

00:21:04.330 --> 00:21:08.500
NARRATOR:
When Morrison examined
the hippocampus of monkeys,

00:21:08.500 --> 00:21:10.730
he found that in young animals,

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:13.900
a single synapse had dozens
of NMDA receptors,

00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:15.630
but in older monkeys,

00:21:15.630 --> 00:21:18.960
the numbers of receptors
dropped sharply.

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:22.100
MORRISON:
Well, it was really amazing,

00:21:22.100 --> 00:21:25.930
because this decrease occurred
in the circuit

00:21:25.930 --> 00:21:30.130
that leads to the ability to
learn and remember new things--

00:21:30.130 --> 00:21:33.760
the classic form of memory
that's affected in aging.

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:38.300
This is, to me,
an optimistic scenario,

00:21:38.300 --> 00:21:41.230
because now we have
a molecular target

00:21:41.230 --> 00:21:44.100
that could potentially
be manipulated

00:21:44.100 --> 00:21:47.630
to restore the health
of that memory circuit.

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:50.330
You guys can start staining
for the light microscopy.

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:53.400
NARRATOR:
Morrison is trying
to develop drugs

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:56.800
to replenish the lost receptors
and rejuvenate failing memories.

00:21:56.800 --> 00:21:58.100
So that will give us
a receptor

00:21:58.100 --> 00:21:59.560
and a presynaptic
marker.

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:02.860
NARRATOR:
But the brain,
scientists are learning,

00:22:02.860 --> 00:22:06.460
has ways to rejuvenate itself.

00:22:06.460 --> 00:22:09.030
93-year-old Milton Adamson

00:22:09.030 --> 00:22:12.930
has exercised regularly
since he was 42.

00:22:12.930 --> 00:22:19.100
On memory tests, he does as well
as people half his age.

00:22:19.100 --> 00:22:24.130
I feel that the mind, uh,
does not lose its ability

00:22:24.130 --> 00:22:27.160
as quickly if you exercise.

00:22:27.160 --> 00:22:32.360
ALBERT:
We never used to think
that physical activity

00:22:32.360 --> 00:22:34.630
was good for the brain
until really very recently

00:22:34.630 --> 00:22:36.560
and there was a large study
that was done

00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:39.830
where they took over
1,000 people in the community

00:22:39.830 --> 00:22:41.460
and looked at the things

00:22:41.460 --> 00:22:44.530
that predicted what helped them
maintain mental ability,

00:22:44.530 --> 00:22:47.760
and it turned out that physical
activity was one of them.

00:22:47.760 --> 00:22:49.130
ADAMSON (<i> on phone</i> ):
Yeah, well,

00:22:49.130 --> 00:22:50.330
we'll get
involved with that

00:22:50.330 --> 00:22:51.860
in the next week or so,

00:22:51.860 --> 00:22:54.830
because I just got a call today
from Burns Nugent, uh, asking me

00:22:54.830 --> 00:22:56.500
to be present
at the next meeting,

00:22:56.500 --> 00:22:58.000
which is a week from Thursday.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:22:59.900
NARRATOR:
Milton has been tested

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:02.460
at the University of California
at Irvine,

00:23:02.460 --> 00:23:05.400
where scientists are searching
for the biochemical keys

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:07.560
to successful aging.

00:23:07.560 --> 00:23:10.460
MAN:
The biggest revolution is,
we've gone

00:23:10.460 --> 00:23:12.230
from describing
what's going wrong

00:23:12.230 --> 00:23:14.360
to getting deep down
into the mechanisms

00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:16.100
to tell what can you do about it

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:20.630
and how can you put more quality
into the life of a neuron.

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:24.460
NARRATOR:
Carl Cotman theorized
that exercise might help

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:25.760
to keep neurons healthy

00:23:25.760 --> 00:23:29.430
by boosting production
of vital brain proteins.

00:23:29.430 --> 00:23:33.160
To test his theory,
he compared two groups of rats.

00:23:33.160 --> 00:23:36.060
While one group sat idly
in their cages,

00:23:36.060 --> 00:23:39.160
the other group
spent hours a day running.

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:41.260
COTMAN:
They jump into
these running wheels

00:23:41.260 --> 00:23:42.900
and they go like gangbusters
around

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:45.430
and they even do little tricks
in the running wheels.

00:23:45.430 --> 00:23:48.100
And then you say, "Well,
what happens to the brain now?"

00:23:48.100 --> 00:23:52.830
NARRATOR:
After eight days, Cotman found
that in the running rats,

00:23:52.830 --> 00:23:57.130
levels of a protein that helps
neurons grow, called "BDNF,"

00:23:57.130 --> 00:24:01.800
had doubled in a part of the
brain that's critical to memory.

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:03.630
COTMAN:
The surprising bottom line

00:24:03.630 --> 00:24:07.000
is that exercise will induce
all kinds of wonderful molecules

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:10.930
that keep neurons healthier,
they keep them stronger.

00:24:10.930 --> 00:24:13.760
They're basically
molecular fertilizer,

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:17.960
and running actually increases
these molecules in the brain.

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:24.630
NARRATOR:
As knowledge of
the aging brain deepens,

00:24:24.630 --> 00:24:26.300
a new portrait is emerging

00:24:26.300 --> 00:24:29.800
of an organ that's resilient
and resourceful,

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:33.130
whose lifetime of experience
may provide it

00:24:33.130 --> 00:24:35.060
with a unique advantage.

00:24:35.060 --> 00:24:38.330
PARK:
Younger people seek out
more information,

00:24:38.330 --> 00:24:39.960
and that's what they're good at.

00:24:39.960 --> 00:24:42.560
They're good at processing
and seeking information.

00:24:42.560 --> 00:24:46.430
Older people are good at mulling
over situations, reflecting

00:24:46.430 --> 00:24:49.300
and using and drawing
upon their experiences,

00:24:49.300 --> 00:24:52.760
and I think that's
what wisdom is.

00:24:52.760 --> 00:24:55.060
(<i> crowd applauding, whistling</i> )

00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:59.730
NARRATOR:
Stanley Kunitz
is America's poet laureate.

00:25:05.500 --> 00:25:09.300
Still writing
and reading his poems,

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:14.200
a mentor to younger poets,
he is 95 years old.

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:17.760
KUNITZ:
"How shall the heart
be reconciled

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:22.960
"to its feast of losses?

00:25:22.960 --> 00:25:29.630
"In a rising wind,
the manic dust of my friends,

00:25:29.630 --> 00:25:37.430
"Those who fell along the way,
bitterly stings my face.

00:25:37.430 --> 00:25:43.630
"Yet I turn, I turn,
exulting somewhat

00:25:43.630 --> 00:25:50.000
"With my will intact to go,
wherever I need to go,

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:55.360
and every stone on the road
precious to me."

00:25:55.360 --> 00:25:59.430
WOMAN:
Mr. Kunitz, that was
absolutely wonderful.

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:04.730
There we are
and here's your lovely pen.

00:26:04.730 --> 00:26:05.730
Thank you.

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:07.230
Thank you.

00:26:07.230 --> 00:26:09.960
MAN:
We were really in the woods
20 years ago.

00:26:09.960 --> 00:26:12.560
We didn't understand
the fundamental nature

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:14.060
of brain aging.

00:26:14.060 --> 00:26:16.060
We thought that to get senile--

00:26:16.060 --> 00:26:18.360
to sort of lose your marbles
as you got older--

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:19.930
was just a normal part of life.

00:26:19.930 --> 00:26:23.400
That's really not
how brain aging works.

00:26:23.400 --> 00:26:27.200
There was such a great pulse
of affection coming back

00:26:27.200 --> 00:26:30.200
from that audience,
it was hard to resist.

00:26:30.200 --> 00:26:32.930
And I loved hearing
about your mother.

00:26:32.930 --> 00:26:34.760
Stanley, if all
of my patients

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:36.660
were like you,
I'd be starving.

00:26:36.660 --> 00:26:38.460
I've been thinking
about you.

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:40.630
KUNITZ:
Sometimes a name slips you.

00:26:40.630 --> 00:26:42.360
That seems to be the most...

00:26:42.360 --> 00:26:45.530
or you don't remember
where you put something down.

00:26:45.530 --> 00:26:50.930
Little, occasional bits
of memory, um, vanish

00:26:50.930 --> 00:26:52.660
from the screen.

00:26:52.660 --> 00:26:59.230
On the other hand, some memories
go deeper than ever before.

00:26:59.230 --> 00:27:05.160
They are profoundly embedded

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:09.930
in your whole psychic structure.

00:27:09.930 --> 00:27:12.830
They form a constellation

00:27:12.830 --> 00:27:17.600
that is at the center
of your imagination.

00:27:20.360 --> 00:27:25.060
"Summer is late, my heart.

00:27:25.060 --> 00:27:32.400
"Words plucked out of the air
some forty years ago

00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:38.530
"When I was wild with love
and torn almost in two

00:27:38.530 --> 00:27:49.200
"scatter like leaves this night
of whistling wind and rain.

00:27:49.200 --> 00:27:58.200
It is my heart that's late,
it is my song that's flown."

00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:05.500
TAUB:
Some people's brains
will age slowly,

00:28:05.500 --> 00:28:07.830
some will age more rapidly.

00:28:07.830 --> 00:28:13.360
A big factor is the genetic
factor-- what's built in.

00:28:13.360 --> 00:28:19.230
The other factor
is the maintenance of activity,

00:28:19.230 --> 00:28:21.900
and if the aging person
remains active,

00:28:21.900 --> 00:28:24.500
there's ample evidence
to indicate

00:28:24.500 --> 00:28:27.030
that his intellectual
functioning

00:28:27.030 --> 00:28:29.400
will decrease
at a much slower rate

00:28:29.400 --> 00:28:31.500
and maybe not decrease at all.

00:28:35.430 --> 00:28:42.660
KUNITZ:
Poetry is an exercise of the
spirit... the spirit within one,

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:50.630
and every time you exercise it,
you increase your vitality.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:57.300
INTERVIEWER:
Most people
aren't poets.

00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:59.560
They may
enjoy poetry...

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:03.060
So what do they do
if they're not poets

00:29:03.060 --> 00:29:05.400
to stay vital
and connected

00:29:05.400 --> 00:29:07.500
and as alive
as you are?

00:29:07.500 --> 00:29:18.160
To care about the life, to care
about others, to remain active.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:26.360
For example, you plant a seed,
you cultivate the soil,

00:29:26.360 --> 00:29:28.460
you watch it flower.

00:29:31.260 --> 00:29:37.400
You're participating in an
ancient ritual of life itself.

00:29:40.600 --> 00:29:45.260
"I kneeled to the crickets
trilling underfoot

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:49.560
"as if about to burst
from their crusty shells;

00:29:49.560 --> 00:29:56.900
"and like a child again
marveled to hear so clear

00:29:56.900 --> 00:30:04.400
"and brave a music pour
from such a small machine.

00:30:04.400 --> 00:30:08.900
"What makes the engine go?

00:30:08.900 --> 00:30:14.730
Desire, desire, desire."

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:28.100
NARRATOR:
As scientists learn more
about how the aging brain works,

00:30:28.100 --> 00:30:31.000
they are overturning some
of the central dogmas

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:32.460
of neuroscience itself.

00:30:36.260 --> 00:30:40.160
For decades, neuroscientists
believed that neurons

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:44.300
in a fully developed brain
never reproduce themselves

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:46.400
and can never be replaced.

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:50.360
MAN:
The idea was that the brain
is a very complex structure.

00:30:50.360 --> 00:30:52.660
It's involved in learning
and memory

00:30:52.660 --> 00:30:55.930
and storing large... large
amounts of information.

00:30:55.930 --> 00:30:58.730
And if you were adding
new neurons

00:30:58.730 --> 00:31:01.100
into the circuit over time,

00:31:01.100 --> 00:31:05.360
it would somehow disrupt
the function of the brain.

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:10.730
NARRATOR:
But in 1998 at the Salk
Institute in California,

00:31:10.730 --> 00:31:12.730
neuroscientist Fred Gage
and his colleagues

00:31:12.730 --> 00:31:15.700
discovered that even
into old age,

00:31:15.700 --> 00:31:20.000
the human brain continues
producing new neurons.

00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:25.830
Like the neurons
that form a baby's brain,

00:31:25.830 --> 00:31:29.500
they are created
by the division of stem cells--

00:31:29.500 --> 00:31:34.030
the seeds from which the tissues
of the body grow.

00:31:34.030 --> 00:31:35.730
Everybody was astonished

00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:39.300
that our brain makes
new nerve cells late in life.

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:40.800
The assumption was

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:43.160
that you had all the nerve
cells you were going to have

00:31:43.160 --> 00:31:45.360
when you were younger,
and then you would lose them

00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:47.260
and you would never be able
to replace them.

00:31:50.060 --> 00:31:54.130
NARRATOR:
Stem cells in an embryonic brain
are wildly prolific,

00:31:54.130 --> 00:31:57.330
producing hundreds
of different kinds of neurons,

00:31:57.330 --> 00:32:04.830
enabling us to see, smell,
walk, think, remember.

00:32:04.830 --> 00:32:08.860
But in an adult brain,
very few neurons are produced.

