00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:38.900
WOMAN:
Here, I'll replicate it.

00:45:38.900 --> 00:45:42.000
COTMAN:
Yeah, see, and then this is
a really diffuse deposit, here.

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:43.500
WOMAN:
Here's a good
diffuse one.

00:45:43.500 --> 00:45:45.330
COTMAN:
This is actually representative

00:45:45.330 --> 00:45:47.230
of almost all three stages,
isn't it?

00:45:47.230 --> 00:45:50.600
NARRATOR:
In labs all across the world,
neuroscientists are closing in

00:45:50.600 --> 00:45:52.360
on the mystery
that has baffled them

00:45:52.360 --> 00:45:54.000
for nearly a century:

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:57.100
What causes Alzheimer's disease?

00:45:58.430 --> 00:46:01.400
Alzheimer's disease
ravages the brain,

00:46:01.400 --> 00:46:05.130
killing billions of neurons,
leaving in its wake

00:46:05.130 --> 00:46:08.730
dark, twisted filaments
called tangles

00:46:08.730 --> 00:46:13.100
and large, sticky masses
called plaques.

00:46:13.100 --> 00:46:17.330
For decades, scientists had
no idea where they came from.

00:46:17.330 --> 00:46:19.030
SELKOE:
It took so long to figure out

00:46:19.030 --> 00:46:20.800
the beginnings
of Alzheimer's disease

00:46:20.800 --> 00:46:23.060
because the brain scientists--

00:46:23.060 --> 00:46:25.730
who understood
what Alzheimer's looked like

00:46:25.730 --> 00:46:27.200
under the microscope--

00:46:27.200 --> 00:46:29.830
didn't think
that these plaques and tangles

00:46:29.830 --> 00:46:33.100
were going to turn out to be
the key to the disease.

00:46:33.100 --> 00:46:35.330
They thought they were
tombstones of the process.

00:46:37.960 --> 00:46:41.030
NARRATOR:
But in the 1980s,
scientists took advantage

00:46:41.030 --> 00:46:43.460
of new technologies
to look more closely.

00:46:43.460 --> 00:46:46.460
They began to suspect
that tangles and plaques

00:46:46.460 --> 00:46:51.230
were more than just tombstones--
they were killers.

00:46:52.430 --> 00:46:54.900
Neurons depend
for their survival

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:58.760
on long chains of molecules
arrayed like railroad tracks

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:01.800
that transport nourishment
across the cell.

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:05.900
What keeps the tracks stable

00:47:05.900 --> 00:47:09.030
are short strips of protein
called tau

00:47:09.030 --> 00:47:11.530
that work like railroad ties.

00:47:11.530 --> 00:47:13.530
In Alzheimer's disease,

00:47:13.530 --> 00:47:17.530
the tau mysteriously starts
to curl and tangle,

00:47:17.530 --> 00:47:21.860
causing the strands of molecules
to separate and collapse.

00:47:23.100 --> 00:47:24.400
These things become twisted,

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:26.230
and they just don't transport
very well.

00:47:26.230 --> 00:47:28.500
You know, it's like somebody
took the train track

00:47:28.500 --> 00:47:29.960
and went... eeyah!

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:32.030
You know, try and get a train
to run along<i> that.</i>

00:47:32.030 --> 00:47:33.100
It can't-- it falls off.

00:47:33.100 --> 00:47:35.060
If the material can't get

00:47:35.060 --> 00:47:36.730
where it needs to be,

00:47:36.730 --> 00:47:39.630
the cell is really going
to collapse

00:47:39.630 --> 00:47:40.830
and eventually die.

00:47:42.060 --> 00:47:44.060
Looking at the cell

00:47:44.060 --> 00:47:47.260
late in the course
of Alzheimer's disease,

00:47:47.260 --> 00:47:52.760
you see a cell that's literally
choked with tangles of tau.

00:47:52.760 --> 00:47:57.630
Now, tangle formation
is a long, slow process.

00:47:57.630 --> 00:47:59.930
That may be a very good thing,

00:47:59.930 --> 00:48:04.560
because if we could interfere
with tangle formation

00:48:04.560 --> 00:48:08.760
early in the disease,
what we may be able to do

00:48:08.760 --> 00:48:12.530
is prevent the progression
of the disease.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:16.230
NARRATOR:
Neuroscientist
Peter Davies thinks

00:48:16.230 --> 00:48:18.200
he may have found
one of the triggers

00:48:18.200 --> 00:48:20.600
that causes tangles to form--

00:48:20.600 --> 00:48:23.930
a protein inside the neuron
called PIN 1.

00:48:23.930 --> 00:48:27.660
DAVIES:
It binds to tau and bends tau,

00:48:27.660 --> 00:48:30.960
actually changes
the shape of tau.

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:35.960
What we would like to do
is to test the idea

00:48:35.960 --> 00:48:40.560
that if we block the effect...
action of PIN 1 on tau,

00:48:40.560 --> 00:48:44.600
we'll actually stop
the tau becoming abnormal

00:48:44.600 --> 00:48:46.930
and becoming tangled tau.

00:48:50.930 --> 00:48:55.560
NARRATOR:
Davies has begun work
developing a drug to stop PIN 1.

00:48:55.560 --> 00:48:57.760
But while he and others
take aim at tangles,

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:01.530
another group of scientists
is targeting plaques.

00:49:04.930 --> 00:49:07.430
In the spaces between neurons

00:49:07.430 --> 00:49:10.800
drift thousands
of molecules of protein.

00:49:10.800 --> 00:49:13.300
In an Alzheimer's brain,
some of them

00:49:13.300 --> 00:49:18.130
are suspicious protein fragments
called beta amyloid.

00:49:18.130 --> 00:49:22.830
Sticky and resilient, bits
of beta amyloid clump together

00:49:22.830 --> 00:49:26.300
to form an expanding mass
called a plaque,

00:49:26.300 --> 00:49:28.530
which attaches itself
like a barnacle

00:49:28.530 --> 00:49:30.360
to the outside of the neuron.

00:49:31.500 --> 00:49:33.230
Sensing a hostile invader,

00:49:33.230 --> 00:49:35.830
the brain's defensive cells
fight back,

00:49:35.830 --> 00:49:38.300
releasing powerful chemicals.

00:49:38.300 --> 00:49:40.760
But the counterattack backfires.

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:43.760
The chemicals set off
a series of reactions

00:49:43.760 --> 00:49:46.000
that slowly destroy the neuron.

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:52.500
When the brain tries to defend
itself from beta amyloid,

00:49:52.500 --> 00:49:55.030
it seems to not get it
quite right.

00:49:55.030 --> 00:49:57.160
It seems to cause
even more of a mess.

00:49:57.160 --> 00:50:02.300
NARRATOR:
As the damage spreads,
more and more neurons die,

00:50:02.300 --> 00:50:07.030
leaving whole regions of
the brain infested with plaques.

00:50:07.030 --> 00:50:08.530
It doesn't
perfectly co-migrate

00:50:08.530 --> 00:50:09.760
with any
of the other bands.

00:50:09.760 --> 00:50:11.260
So it's a little bit
tough to say.

00:50:11.260 --> 00:50:12.930
So these
are her stable
transfectants?

00:50:12.930 --> 00:50:16.100
NARRATOR:
Scientists
like Dennis Selkoe theorize

00:50:16.100 --> 00:50:19.530
that lowering the amount
of beta amyloid in the brain

00:50:19.530 --> 00:50:22.530
may prevent Alzheimer's disease,

00:50:22.530 --> 00:50:24.300
just as lowering levels
of cholesterol

00:50:24.300 --> 00:50:25.700
prevents heart disease.

00:50:27.100 --> 00:50:29.300
SELKOE:
The trouble is
that it's not so easy,

00:50:29.300 --> 00:50:31.730
because, number one,
the theory might be wrong--

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:34.430
it's a hypothesis, not a fact--

00:50:34.430 --> 00:50:37.230
and number two,
even if it's right,

00:50:37.230 --> 00:50:39.060
it may be trouble
to lower amyloid.

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:41.760
It may cause side effects.

00:50:41.760 --> 00:50:44.030
But experimental work
that's been done

00:50:44.030 --> 00:50:45.960
in many laboratories worldwide

00:50:45.960 --> 00:50:48.460
supports
this hypothesis strongly.

00:50:48.460 --> 00:50:50.200
And the proof will come

00:50:50.200 --> 00:50:52.830
from lowering beta amyloid
in people

00:50:52.830 --> 00:50:55.060
and watching their Alzheimer's
get better.

00:50:59.400 --> 00:51:02.960
NARRATOR:
In a pharmaceutical lab
near San Francisco,

00:51:02.960 --> 00:51:07.900
neuroscientist Dale Schenk has
taken a step toward that goal

00:51:07.900 --> 00:51:10.130
with a strategy
that surprised many scientists.

00:51:11.800 --> 00:51:16.630
SCHENK:
The novelty was to use
the immune system

00:51:16.630 --> 00:51:19.930
to treat Alzheimer's disease--

00:51:19.930 --> 00:51:22.160
to try to tell
the immune system, in fact,

00:51:22.160 --> 00:51:25.830
that this plaque material
in the brain is foreign

00:51:25.830 --> 00:51:28.230
and our immune system
needs to get rid of it.

00:51:28.230 --> 00:51:34.630
NARRATOR:
Schenk developed a vaccine
made from beta amyloid itself

00:51:34.630 --> 00:51:37.630
and tested it
on genetically engineered mice

00:51:37.630 --> 00:51:41.700
bred to develop plaques like
those in Alzheimer's disease.

00:51:41.700 --> 00:51:45.430
Well, as it turned out,
to our huge surprise,

00:51:45.430 --> 00:51:49.400
when we immunized them
from a young age onward,

00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:50.800
and then looked at an old age--

00:51:50.800 --> 00:51:53.130
when they should have a lot
of plaque lesions--

00:51:53.130 --> 00:51:54.400
they had almost none.

00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:56.700
Their brain
was almost entirely perfect.

00:51:58.230 --> 00:52:00.960
NARRATOR:
Encouraged by his findings,
Schenk wondered

00:52:00.960 --> 00:52:02.930
if the vaccine
might eliminate plaques

00:52:02.930 --> 00:52:05.260
that had already formed
in older mice.

00:52:06.430 --> 00:52:09.060
He vaccinated one group
of older mice

00:52:09.060 --> 00:52:12.030
but left a control group
untreated.

00:52:12.030 --> 00:52:15.260
He found that the brains
of the mice in the control group

00:52:15.260 --> 00:52:16.930
were ravaged by plaque,

00:52:16.930 --> 00:52:19.230
but the brains
of the vaccinated mice

00:52:19.230 --> 00:52:21.130
had almost no plaques at all.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:25.430
In the beginning,
I was skeptical.

00:52:25.430 --> 00:52:28.100
And then I saw the data.

00:52:28.100 --> 00:52:31.400
And the data are very good,
and they're very persuasive.

00:52:31.400 --> 00:52:33.500
And that's
why everybody's very excited.

00:52:36.560 --> 00:52:40.430
NARRATOR:
But establishing the safety
and effectiveness of the vaccine

00:52:40.430 --> 00:52:42.660
and other new treatments
for Alzheimer's

00:52:42.660 --> 00:52:45.130
will require years of testing.

00:52:47.030 --> 00:52:50.060
HIATT:
I'm hoping at least I can
hang on long enough

00:52:50.060 --> 00:52:52.860
that somebody can make
a breakthrough to figure out

00:52:52.860 --> 00:52:56.700
how to take care of this stuff.

00:52:56.700 --> 00:52:58.930
Right now, I really
don't have much fear.

00:52:58.930 --> 00:53:01.800
I think that what concern,
though, is the future--

00:53:01.800 --> 00:53:04.530
what's five years from now,
or ten years from now.

00:53:04.530 --> 00:53:08.930
HIATT:
Okay, I'm not going
to cut any more today.

00:53:08.930 --> 00:53:10.500
Enough.

00:53:10.500 --> 00:53:13.160
ALBERT:
I really thought that in my
lifetime, I wouldn't see

00:53:13.160 --> 00:53:15.200
effective treatments
for Alzheimer's disease.

00:53:15.200 --> 00:53:19.930
And I believe now
that in my lifetime I will.

00:53:19.930 --> 00:53:23.460
DOTTIE:
Let me start here
on this end, please?

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:24.500
HIATT:
Okay.

00:53:30.630 --> 00:53:34.260
KUNITZ:
In my darkest night

00:53:34.260 --> 00:53:40.530
When the moon was covered
And I roamed through wreckage

00:53:40.530 --> 00:53:45.700
A nimbus-clouded voice
Directed me:

00:53:45.700 --> 00:53:54.260
"Live in the layers
Not on the litter."

00:53:54.260 --> 00:53:58.000
Though I lack the art
to decipher it,

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:05.360
no doubt the next chapter
in my book of transformations

00:54:05.360 --> 00:54:07.560
Is already written.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:17.200
I am not done with my changes.

